{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774409303,"nonce":"LnkUAFV5ZCSWWo0MKueePYfenIs=","message":"**Implication for training task design**\n\nIf all position inputs are expressed relative to start position, the absolute start position drops out of the network's input space entirely. This means:\n\n1. The training task reduces to sampling reach vectors (direction + amplitude) rather than (start, target) pairs in a workspace.\n2. All reaches become effectively center-out from the origin in the network's coordinate frame.\n3. The workspace concept becomes irrelevant to the network — only the reach vector matters.\n4. This removes a dimension of spurious variation that the network currently wastes capacity learning to ignore.\n\nCurrent training does randomly sample start and target points within a workspace ([-1,1]^2). With relative inputs, this is equivalent to sampling random reach vectors, but the absolute position information is carried through as dead weight in the current representation.\n\nThe fix is straightforward: subtract start position from all position-valued inputs (effector pos, target pos) before feeding to the network. The dynamics (F=ma for point mass) are unchanged.","files":null}]}